[
  {
    id: 1,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Basic Service class definition",
    instruction: "How do I define a basic Ember Service class?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class ScoreService extends Service {\n  fetchLiveScore() {\n    return fetch('/api/score');\n  }\n}\n```\nA service extends `Service` from `@ember/service` and is exported as the default export. The class name becomes the service's registered name in the container (e.g., `ScoreService` → `score`). Services are singletons — one instance per application lifecycle.",
  },
  {
    id: 2,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with a @tracked property",
    instruction: "How do I add a @tracked property to an Ember Service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class MatchService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentMatch = null;\n}\n```\nImport `tracked` from `@glimmer/tracking` and decorate any property that should trigger reactivity when changed. All consuming components and templates that read `this.currentMatch` will automatically re-render when the property is updated.",
  },
  {
    id: 3,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with multiple @tracked properties",
    instruction:
      "Show me a service with multiple @tracked properties for cricket match state.",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class LiveScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked runs = 0;\n  @tracked wickets = 0;\n  @tracked over = '0.0';\n  @tracked battingTeam = null;\n  @tracked bowlingTeam = null;\n  @tracked isLive = false;\n}\n```\nEach `@tracked` property is tracked independently. Changing `this.runs` does not cause templates reading only `this.wickets` to re-render — Glimmer's tracking is property-level granular.",
  },
  {
    id: 4,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with a plain (non-tracked) property",
    instruction: "How do I add a plain, non-reactive property to a service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class ApiService extends Service {\n  baseUrl = 'https://api.spordium.com/v2';\n  timeout = 5000;\n\n  buildUrl(path) {\n    return `${this.baseUrl}${path}`;\n  }\n}\n```\nProperties without `@tracked` are plain JavaScript class fields. They work fine for configuration values and constants that never need to trigger re-renders. Only add `@tracked` when you need the UI to react to changes.",
  },
  {
    id: 5,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with a regular method",
    instruction: "How do I add a regular method to a service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class PlayerService extends Service {\n  @tracked selectedPlayer = null;\n\n  selectPlayer(player) {\n    this.selectedPlayer = player;\n  }\n\n  clearSelection() {\n    this.selectedPlayer = null;\n  }\n}\n```\nRegular methods on a service are plain ES2024 class methods. They can read and write `@tracked` properties freely. Unlike component actions, service methods do not need the `@action` decorator — there is no this-binding issue when they are called from other service methods.",
  },
  {
    id: 6,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with an async method using async/await",
    instruction:
      "How do I write an async method in a service using async/await?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class MatchService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentMatch = null;\n  @tracked isLoading = false;\n  @tracked error = null;\n\n  async loadMatch(matchId) {\n    this.isLoading = true;\n    this.error = null;\n    try {\n      const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`);\n      if (!response.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);\n      this.currentMatch = await response.json();\n    } catch (err) {\n      this.error = err.message;\n    } finally {\n      this.isLoading = false;\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\nAsync methods work normally in services. Always wrap in try/catch and reset loading state in `finally`. Note that plain async methods are not cancellable — prefer ember-concurrency tasks when cancellation is needed.",
  },
  {
    id: 7,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with a task() from ember-concurrency",
    instruction: "How do I add an ember-concurrency task to a service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class ScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked score = null;\n\n  fetchScore = task(async (matchId) => {\n    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`);\n    if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Failed to fetch score');\n    this.score = await response.json();\n  });\n}\n```\nDefine tasks as class field assignments using the `task()` helper. Tasks are automatically cancellable, expose `.isRunning`, `.last`, and `.perform()`. They integrate cleanly with Glimmer reactivity without extra boilerplate.",
  },
  {
    id: 8,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with a drop task",
    instruction:
      "How do I create a drop task in a service to prevent duplicate API calls?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class FixtureService extends Service {\n  @tracked fixtures = [];\n\n  loadFixtures = task({ drop: true }, async (tournamentId) => {\n    const response = await fetch(`/api/tournaments/${tournamentId}/fixtures`);\n    if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Failed');\n    this.fixtures = await response.json();\n  });\n}\n```\nPassing `{ drop: true }` as the first argument makes the task drop any new `.perform()` calls while an instance is already running. This prevents duplicate network requests when a component mounts multiple times or a button is clicked rapidly.",
  },
  {
    id: 9,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with a restartable task",
    instruction:
      "How do I create a restartable task in a service for live search?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class SearchService extends Service {\n  @tracked results = [];\n\n  search = task({ restartable: true }, async (query) => {\n    await timeout(300);\n    const response = await fetch(`/api/search?q=${encodeURIComponent(query)}`);\n    if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Search failed');\n    this.results = await response.json();\n  });\n}\n```\nThe `{ restartable: true }` modifier cancels any running instance when `.perform()` is called again. Combined with `timeout(300)` for debouncing, this is the standard pattern for search-as-you-type functionality in a service.",
  },
  {
    id: 10,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with a getter computed from @tracked",
    instruction:
      "How do I add a getter to a service that computes from @tracked state?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked runs = 0;\n  @tracked wickets = 0;\n  @tracked totalOvers = 20;\n  @tracked currentOver = 0;\n\n  get runRate() {\n    if (this.currentOver === 0) return 0;\n    return (this.runs / this.currentOver).toFixed(2);\n  }\n\n  get isAllOut() {\n    return this.wickets >= 10;\n  }\n\n  get oversRemaining() {\n    return this.totalOvers - this.currentOver;\n  }\n}\n```\nGetters in services are automatically tracked — they re-evaluate whenever any `@tracked` property they read changes. All consuming components will receive the updated value reactively without any manual notification.",
  },
  {
    id: 11,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with setter",
    instruction:
      "How do I write a setter on a service to validate before updating @tracked state?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked _runs = 0;\n\n  get runs() {\n    return this._runs;\n  }\n\n  set runs(value) {\n    if (typeof value !== 'number' || value < 0) {\n      console.warn('Invalid runs value:', value);\n      return;\n    }\n    this._runs = value;\n  }\n}\n```\nUse a private `@tracked _runs` backing field and expose `get`/`set` accessors for validation. The setter guards against invalid values while the getter returns the tracked field. Consumers read and write `service.runs` naturally.",
  },
  {
    id: 12,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Injecting a service into a component with @service decorator",
    instruction: "How do I inject a service into a GJS component?",
    response:
      "```gjs\nimport Component from '@glimmer/component';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class ScoreBoardComponent extends Component {\n  @service score;\n\n  <template>\n    <div class=\"scoreboard\">\n      <p>Runs: {{this.score.runs}}</p>\n      <p>Wickets: {{this.score.wickets}}</p>\n    </div>\n  </template>\n}\n```\nImport `service` from `@ember/service` and use it as a decorator on a class field. The field name (`score`) must match the service's registered name. Ember resolves the service from the application container and injects the singleton instance.",
  },
  {
    id: 13,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Injecting multiple services into one component",
    instruction:
      "Show me how to inject multiple services into a single GJS component.",
    response:
      "```gjs\nimport Component from '@glimmer/component';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\nimport { action } from '@ember/object';\n\nexport default class MatchPageComponent extends Component {\n  @service auth;\n  @service match;\n  @service notification;\n  @service router;\n\n  @action\n  async loadAndNavigate(matchId) {\n    if (!this.auth.isAuthenticated) {\n      this.notification.error('Please log in first');\n      this.router.transitionTo('login');\n      return;\n    }\n    await this.match.loadMatch.perform(matchId);\n  }\n\n  <template>\n    <div>{{this.match.currentMatch.title}}</div>\n  </template>\n}\n```\nEach `@service` decorated field receives its own singleton reference. All services are injected lazily at first access. Multiple services can collaborate inside a single action method.",
  },
  {
    id: 14,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Injecting a service into another service",
    instruction: "How do I inject one service into another service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class MatchService extends Service {\n  @service notification;\n  @service router;\n\n  loadMatch = task({ drop: true }, async (matchId) => {\n    try {\n      const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`);\n      if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Match not found');\n      return response.json();\n    } catch (err) {\n      this.notification.error(err.message);\n      this.router.transitionTo('matches');\n    }\n  });\n}\n```\nThe `@service` decorator works identically inside services and components. Services are singletons, so injecting `notification` into `match` gives access to the same notification service instance used by the entire app.",
  },
  {
    id: 15,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Injecting the router service",
    instruction:
      "How do I use the router service in a component for programmatic navigation?",
    response:
      "```gjs\nimport Component from '@glimmer/component';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\nimport { action } from '@ember/object';\n\nexport default class MatchCardComponent extends Component {\n  @service router;\n\n  @action\n  goToMatch() {\n    this.router.transitionTo('match.detail', this.args.match.id);\n  }\n\n  @action\n  goToPlayer(playerId) {\n    this.router.transitionTo('player.profile', playerId);\n  }\n\n  <template>\n    <div class=\"match-card\">\n      <h2>{{@match.title}}</h2>\n      <button type=\"button\" {{on \"click\" this.goToMatch}}>View Match</button>\n    </div>\n  </template>\n}\n```\nThe built-in `router` service provides `transitionTo`, `replaceWith`, `currentRouteName`, and `urlFor`. It is the preferred way to navigate programmatically in Ember — never manipulate `window.location` directly.",
  },
  {
    id: 16,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Injecting the store service (Ember Data)",
    instruction: "How do I inject the Ember Data store into a component?",
    response:
      "```gjs\nimport Component from '@glimmer/component';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\nimport { action } from '@ember/object';\n\nexport default class PlayerListComponent extends Component {\n  @service store;\n\n  get players() {\n    return this.store.peekAll('player');\n  }\n\n  @action\n  async loadPlayers() {\n    await this.store.findAll('player');\n  }\n\n  <template>\n    <ul>\n      {{#each this.players as |player|}}\n        <li>{{player.name}}</li>\n      {{/each}}\n    </ul>\n  </template>\n}\n```\nThe `store` service is Ember Data's identity map. `peekAll` returns cached records synchronously. `findAll` and `findRecord` fetch from the server asynchronously. Always use `await` or tasks for async store operations.",
  },
  {
    id: 17,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Injecting a custom service into a route",
    instruction: "How do I inject a custom service into an Ember route?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Route from '@ember/routing/route';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class MatchRoute extends Route {\n  @service matchService;\n  @service auth;\n\n  async beforeModel() {\n    if (!this.auth.isAuthenticated) {\n      this.transitionTo('login');\n    }\n  }\n\n  async model(params) {\n    await this.matchService.loadMatch.perform(params.match_id);\n    return this.matchService.currentMatch;\n  }\n}\n```\nThe `@service` decorator works in routes exactly as in components. Routes are a natural place to load data and guard access before the component tree renders.",
  },
  {
    id: 18,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Accessing service @tracked value in component template",
    instruction:
      "How do I access a service's @tracked property in a GJS template?",
    response:
      '```gjs\nimport Component from \'@glimmer/component\';\nimport { service } from \'@ember/service\';\n\nexport default class LiveScoreComponent extends Component {\n  @service liveScore;\n\n  <template>\n    <div class="live-score p-4 bg-white rounded-xl">\n      <p class="text-3xl font-bold">\n        {{this.liveScore.runs}}/{{this.liveScore.wickets}}\n      </p>\n      <p class="text-gray-500">Over: {{this.liveScore.over}}</p>\n      {{#if this.liveScore.isLive}}\n        <span class="text-green-500">● LIVE</span>\n      {{/if}}\n    </div>\n  </template>\n}\n```\nAccess injected service properties with `this.serviceName.propertyName` in templates. Because `@tracked` properties on services use Glimmer\'s reactivity system, the template automatically re-renders whenever the service\'s tracked state changes.',
  },
  {
    id: 19,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Calling a service method from component @action",
    instruction: "How do I call a service method from a component @action?",
    response:
      "```gjs\nimport Component from '@glimmer/component';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\nimport { action } from '@ember/object';\n\nexport default class PlayerCardComponent extends Component {\n  @service playerService;\n  @service notification;\n\n  @action\n  selectThisPlayer() {\n    this.playerService.selectPlayer(this.args.player);\n    this.notification.success(`${this.args.player.name} selected`);\n  }\n\n  @action\n  clearSelection() {\n    this.playerService.clearSelection();\n  }\n\n  <template>\n    <div class=\"player-card\">\n      <h3>{{@player.name}}</h3>\n      <button type=\"button\" {{on \"click\" this.selectThisPlayer}}>Select</button>\n    </div>\n  </template>\n}\n```\nService methods are plain methods — call them with `this.serviceName.methodName(args)`. The `@action` decorator on the component method ensures correct `this` binding when used as an event handler.",
  },
  {
    id: 20,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Calling a service task.perform() from component @action",
    instruction: "How do I call a service task from a component action?",
    response:
      "```gjs\nimport Component from '@glimmer/component';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\nimport { action } from '@ember/object';\n\nexport default class SearchBarComponent extends Component {\n  @service searchService;\n\n  @action\n  handleInput(event) {\n    this.searchService.search.perform(event.target.value);\n  }\n\n  <template>\n    <input\n      type=\"search\"\n      placeholder=\"Search players, teams...\"\n      {{on \"input\" this.handleInput}}\n    />\n    {{#if this.searchService.search.isRunning}}\n      <span>Searching...</span>\n    {{/if}}\n  </template>\n}\n```\nCall tasks with `.perform()`. The task's `.isRunning` state is reactive — the template automatically shows/hides the loading indicator. The task instance lives on the service, so any component can check `.isRunning`.",
  },
  {
    id: 21,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service willDestroy() — cleanup lifecycle hook",
    instruction: "How do I use willDestroy() in a service for cleanup?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ScrollService extends Service {\n  @tracked scrollTop = 0;\n\n  #handleScroll = () => {\n    this.scrollTop = window.scrollY;\n  };\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    window.addEventListener('scroll', this.#handleScroll);\n  }\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    window.removeEventListener('scroll', this.#handleScroll);\n  }\n}\n```\n`willDestroy` is called when the service is torn down (typically on app destroy). Always call `super.willDestroy()` first. Use it to remove event listeners, close connections, or cancel timers to prevent memory leaks.",
  },
  {
    id: 22,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with willDestroy cancelling a task",
    instruction: "How do I cancel a running task when a service is destroyed?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class PollingService extends Service {\n  pollScore = task({ restartable: true }, async (matchId) => {\n    while (true) {\n      const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`);\n      this.score = await response.json();\n      await timeout(5000);\n    }\n  });\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    this.pollScore.cancelAll();\n  }\n}\n```\nCall `taskInstance.cancelAll()` in `willDestroy` to cancel any running task instances. Without this, an infinite polling loop would continue even after the service is no longer active, causing memory and network leaks.",
  },
  {
    id: 23,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with willDestroy removing event listeners",
    instruction:
      "Show me a service that removes multiple event listeners in willDestroy.",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class NetworkService extends Service {\n  @tracked isOnline = navigator.onLine;\n\n  #onOnline  = () => { this.isOnline = true; };\n  #onOffline = () => { this.isOnline = false; };\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    window.addEventListener('online',  this.#onOnline);\n    window.addEventListener('offline', this.#onOffline);\n  }\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    window.removeEventListener('online',  this.#onOnline);\n    window.removeEventListener('offline', this.#onOffline);\n  }\n}\n```\nStore handler references as private class fields (`#onOnline`) so the same function reference can be passed to both `addEventListener` and `removeEventListener`. Anonymous arrow functions cannot be removed — always store references.",
  },
  {
    id: 24,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service initializing state in constructor",
    instruction: "How do I initialize service state in the constructor?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class SessionService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentUser = null;\n  @tracked token = null;\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    const storedToken = localStorage.getItem('auth_token');\n    const storedUser  = localStorage.getItem('current_user');\n    if (storedToken) {\n      this.token = storedToken;\n      this.currentUser = storedUser ? JSON.parse(storedUser) : null;\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\nThe service constructor receives `owner` and `args` and must call `super(owner, args)`. The constructor runs once when the service is first accessed. It is the right place to restore persisted state from localStorage.",
  },
  {
    id: 25,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service constructor calling super()",
    instruction:
      "Why must I call super() in an Ember Service constructor and what parameters does it take?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class MyService extends Service {\n  // ✅ CORRECT — always call super with owner and args\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    // Your initialization here\n    this.initializeData();\n  }\n\n  initializeData() {\n    // setup logic\n  }\n}\n```\nCalling `super(owner, args)` registers the service with Ember's owner (the application container), which enables service injection, routing, and other framework features. Omitting `super` or calling it without arguments will cause the service to malfunction or throw errors.",
  },
  {
    id: 26,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with a private helper method",
    instruction: "How do I add a private helper method to a service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ApiService extends Service {\n  @tracked data = null;\n\n  async fetchData(endpoint) {\n    const response = await fetch(this.#buildUrl(endpoint), {\n      headers: this.#buildHeaders(),\n    });\n    this.data = await response.json();\n  }\n\n  #buildUrl(path) {\n    return `https://api.spordium.com/v2${path}`;\n  }\n\n  #buildHeaders() {\n    return {\n      'Content-Type': 'application/json',\n      'Accept': 'application/json',\n    };\n  }\n}\n```\nUse the native ES2024 private field syntax (`#methodName`) for helper methods that are implementation details. Private methods cannot be called from outside the class, which enforces a clean public API and prevents accidental misuse.",
  },
  {
    id: 27,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service exposing a read-only getter",
    instruction:
      "How do I expose a read-only getter on a service that hides an internal @tracked field?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class AuthService extends Service {\n  @tracked #currentUser = null;\n\n  get currentUser() {\n    return this.#currentUser;\n  }\n\n  get isAuthenticated() {\n    return this.#currentUser !== null;\n  }\n\n  login(user) {\n    this.#currentUser = user;\n  }\n\n  logout() {\n    this.#currentUser = null;\n  }\n}\n```\nMake the `@tracked` field private (`#currentUser`) and expose it only through a getter. This prevents external code from directly setting the field — all mutations go through `login()` and `logout()` methods, keeping the service in a consistent state.",
  },
  {
    id: 28,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with an array @tracked property",
    instruction:
      "Show me a service with a @tracked array for storing match results.",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ResultsService extends Service {\n  @tracked recentResults = [];\n\n  addResult(result) {\n    this.recentResults = [result, ...this.recentResults];\n  }\n\n  removeResult(id) {\n    this.recentResults = this.recentResults.filter(r => r.id !== id);\n  }\n\n  clearResults() {\n    this.recentResults = [];\n  }\n}\n```\nA `@tracked` array must be replaced (not mutated) to trigger reactivity. Always use spread (`[...arr]`), `filter`, `map`, or `slice` to create a new array, then assign it back to the tracked field. Calling `.push()` directly on the array will not trigger re-renders.",
  },
  {
    id: 29,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service @action method",
    instruction:
      "Can I use @action on a service method, and when would I do that?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { action } from '@ember/object';\n\nexport default class PlayerService extends Service {\n  @tracked selectedPlayer = null;\n\n  // @action ensures correct `this` binding if passed as callback\n  @action\n  selectPlayer(player) {\n    this.selectedPlayer = player;\n  }\n\n  // Regular method — fine when called directly as this.service.method()\n  clearSelection() {\n    this.selectedPlayer = null;\n  }\n}\n```\nService methods generally do not need `@action` because `this` is correctly bound when called as `this.service.method()`. Use `@action` only when you plan to pass the method as a callback reference (e.g., `const handler = this.service.selectPlayer`) without immediately invoking it.",
  },
  {
    id: 30,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service method returning a value",
    instruction:
      "How do I write a service method that computes and returns a value?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class StatsService extends Service {\n  @tracked matches = [];\n\n  getPlayerStats(playerId) {\n    const playerMatches = this.matches.filter(m =>\n      m.batsmen.some(b => b.id === playerId)\n    );\n    const totalRuns = playerMatches.reduce((sum, m) => {\n      const batsman = m.batsmen.find(b => b.id === playerId);\n      return sum + (batsman?.runs ?? 0);\n    }, 0);\n    return { matches: playerMatches.length, totalRuns };\n  }\n}\n```\nService methods can return any value. Callers receive the return value synchronously. For async computations, use a task or async method instead and store the result in a `@tracked` property for template consumption.",
  },
  {
    id: 31,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service method that updates its own @tracked state",
    instruction:
      "Show me a service method that updates its own tracked state after computing a value.",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked runs = 0;\n  @tracked wickets = 0;\n  @tracked ballsPlayed = 0;\n  @tracked runRate = 0;\n\n  recordBall(runsScored, isWicket = false) {\n    this.runs += runsScored;\n    this.ballsPlayed += 1;\n    if (isWicket) this.wickets += 1;\n    const overs = this.ballsPlayed / 6;\n    this.runRate = overs > 0 ? Number((this.runs / overs).toFixed(2)) : 0;\n  }\n}\n```\nA service method can update multiple `@tracked` properties in sequence. Glimmer batches these updates and triggers a single re-render cycle, preventing excessive re-renders when several properties change together.",
  },
  {
    id: 32,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service method that calls another service method",
    instruction:
      "How do I call a method from another injected service inside a service method?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class MatchService extends Service {\n  @service notification;\n  @service analyticsService;\n\n  submitResult = task({ drop: true }, async (matchId, result) => {\n    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/result`, {\n      method: 'POST',\n      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },\n      body: JSON.stringify(result),\n    });\n    if (!response.ok) {\n      this.notification.error('Failed to submit result');\n      return;\n    }\n    this.notification.success('Result submitted!');\n    this.analyticsService.trackEvent('result_submitted', { matchId });\n  });\n}\n```\nService methods freely call methods on other injected services. This enables rich service collaboration without coupling components to the logic.",
  },
  {
    id: 33,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service task that reads its own @tracked state",
    instruction:
      "Show me a service task that reads the service's own @tracked properties.",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class CommentaryService extends Service {\n  @tracked matchId = null;\n  @tracked comments = [];\n\n  fetchLatestComments = task({ drop: true }, async () => {\n    if (!this.matchId) return;\n    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${this.matchId}/commentary`);\n    if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Failed to load commentary');\n    const data = await response.json();\n    this.comments = data.entries;\n  });\n}\n```\nTasks access `this` normally — `this.matchId` reads the current tracked value at the time the task runs. This allows the task to be called without arguments when the required state is already stored on the service.",
  },
  {
    id: 34,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service task that updates its own @tracked state after fetch",
    instruction:
      "Show me a service task that fetches data and updates multiple @tracked properties.",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class PlayerService extends Service {\n  @tracked player = null;\n  @tracked isLoading = false;\n  @tracked error = null;\n\n  fetchPlayer = task({ drop: true }, async (playerId) => {\n    this.isLoading = true;\n    this.error = null;\n    try {\n      const response = await fetch(`/api/players/${playerId}`);\n      if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Player not found');\n      this.player = await response.json();\n    } catch (err) {\n      this.error = err.message;\n    } finally {\n      this.isLoading = false;\n    }\n  });\n}\n```\nTasks update `@tracked` properties naturally using `this.property = value`. The `finally` block ensures `isLoading` resets even on cancellation (though on cancel the catch block handles `TaskCancelation`).",
  },
  {
    id: 35,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service task that calls store.findAll()",
    instruction: "How do I call store.findAll() inside a service task?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class TournamentService extends Service {\n  @service store;\n  @tracked tournaments = [];\n\n  loadTournaments = task({ drop: true }, async () => {\n    const results = await this.store.findAll('tournament');\n    this.tournaments = results.slice();\n  });\n}\n```\nUse `this.store` (injected via `@service store`) inside tasks. `store.findAll` returns an Ember Data LiveArray. Calling `.slice()` converts it to a plain array to avoid proxy-related reactivity issues when storing in `@tracked`.",
  },
  {
    id: 36,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service task that calls store.query() with params",
    instruction:
      "How do I use store.query() with parameters in a service task?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class FixtureService extends Service {\n  @service store;\n  @tracked fixtures = [];\n\n  fetchFixtures = task({ restartable: true }, async ({ tournamentId, format, page = 1 }) => {\n    const results = await this.store.query('fixture', {\n      filter: { tournament: tournamentId, format },\n      page: { number: page, size: 20 },\n    });\n    this.fixtures = results.slice();\n  });\n}\n```\n`store.query` sends a GET request with the provided params as query string. It always hits the server (unlike `peekAll`). The task is `restartable` so rapid filter changes cancel previous in-flight requests.",
  },
  {
    id: 37,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service task that performs a raw fetch() API call",
    instruction:
      "Show me a service task using raw fetch() instead of the Ember Data store.",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class LiveScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked score = null;\n  @tracked error = null;\n\n  fetchLiveScore = task({ drop: true }, async (matchId) => {\n    this.error = null;\n    try {\n      const response = await fetch(`/api/live/${matchId}/score`, {\n        headers: { 'Accept': 'application/json' },\n      });\n      if (!response.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);\n      this.score = await response.json();\n    } catch (err) {\n      this.error = err.message;\n    }\n  });\n}\n```\nRaw `fetch()` is ideal for endpoints not modeled in Ember Data (live scores, analytics, third-party APIs). Always check `response.ok` and handle errors explicitly since `fetch` only rejects on network failure, not HTTP error status codes.",
  },
  {
    id: 38,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service task that handles errors and sets @tracked error",
    instruction:
      "How do I handle errors in a service task and expose them reactively?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class VenueService extends Service {\n  @tracked venues = [];\n  @tracked error = null;\n\n  loadVenues = task({ drop: true }, async () => {\n    this.error = null;\n    try {\n      const response = await fetch('/api/venues');\n      if (!response.ok) throw new Error(`Failed to load venues: ${response.status}`);\n      const data = await response.json();\n      this.venues = data.venues;\n    } catch (err) {\n      if (err.name !== 'TaskCancelation') {\n        this.error = err.message;\n      }\n    }\n  });\n}\n```\nCheck `err.name !== 'TaskCancelation'` before setting `this.error` — cancellation is intentional and should not show an error message to the user. Always clear `this.error = null` before each attempt so stale errors don't persist.",
  },
  {
    id: 39,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service @tracked array — adding item with spread pattern",
    instruction:
      "How do I add an item to a @tracked array in a service reactively?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class NotificationService extends Service {\n  @tracked notifications = [];\n\n  addNotification(notification) {\n    const id = Date.now();\n    this.notifications = [\n      ...this.notifications,\n      { ...notification, id },\n    ];\n    return id;\n  }\n}\n```\nUse spread (`[...existing, newItem]`) to create a new array reference, which triggers Glimmer's reactivity. Never call `.push()` directly on a `@tracked` array — mutation without reassignment does not trigger re-renders.",
  },
  {
    id: 40,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service @tracked array — removing item with filter pattern",
    instruction: "How do I remove an item from a @tracked array in a service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class NotificationService extends Service {\n  @tracked notifications = [];\n\n  removeNotification(id) {\n    this.notifications = this.notifications.filter(n => n.id !== id);\n  }\n\n  clearAll() {\n    this.notifications = [];\n  }\n}\n```\n`Array.filter()` returns a new array, satisfying Glimmer's requirement for a new reference. The original array is not mutated. Assign the filtered result back to the `@tracked` property to trigger re-renders in all consuming templates.",
  },
  {
    id: 41,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service @tracked array — replacing item with map pattern",
    instruction:
      "How do I update a specific item in a @tracked array in a service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class LineupService extends Service {\n  @tracked players = [];\n\n  updatePlayerRuns(playerId, newRuns) {\n    this.players = this.players.map(player =>\n      player.id === playerId\n        ? { ...player, runs: newRuns }\n        : player\n    );\n  }\n}\n```\n`Array.map()` returns a new array where the matching item is replaced with a new spread object. This is the correct pattern for immutable-style updates in Glimmer-tracked arrays. Both the array reference and the object reference are new, ensuring reactivity.",
  },
  {
    id: 42,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service @tracked object — updating a property with spread",
    instruction:
      "How do I update a property on a @tracked object in a service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class MatchService extends Service {\n  @tracked match = null;\n\n  updateScore(runs, wickets, over) {\n    if (!this.match) return;\n    this.match = {\n      ...this.match,\n      score: { runs, wickets, over },\n      updatedAt: new Date().toISOString(),\n    };\n  }\n}\n```\nSpread the existing object and override the changed properties: `{ ...existing, changedKey: newValue }`. This creates a new object reference, which triggers Glimmer reactivity. Mutating `this.match.score.runs = value` directly does not trigger re-renders.",
  },
  {
    id: 43,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with multiple tasks with different concurrency modifiers",
    instruction:
      "Show me a service with three tasks each using a different concurrency modifier.",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class ScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked score = null;\n  @tracked history = [];\n  @tracked searchResults = [];\n\n  // drop: only one load at a time, extras ignored\n  loadScore = task({ drop: true }, async (matchId) => {\n    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`);\n    this.score = await res.json();\n  });\n\n  // enqueue: queues concurrent performs sequentially\n  recordBall = task({ enqueue: true }, async (ballData) => {\n    const res = await fetch('/api/balls', { method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify(ballData) });\n    this.history = [...this.history, await res.json()];\n  });\n\n  // restartable: latest perform cancels previous\n  searchPlayers = task({ restartable: true }, async (query) => {\n    const res = await fetch(`/api/players?q=${query}`);\n    this.searchResults = await res.json();\n  });\n}\n```\nChoose the concurrency modifier based on intent: `drop` for idempotent loads, `enqueue` for ordered writes, `restartable` for latest-wins queries.",
  },
  {
    id: 44,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service method that performs a task and returns the task instance",
    instruction:
      "How do I call a task from a service method and return the task instance?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class MatchService extends Service {\n  loadMatch = task({ drop: true }, async (matchId) => {\n    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`);\n    return response.json();\n  });\n\n  startLoadingMatch(matchId) {\n    // Returns the TaskInstance — callers can await it or check .isRunning\n    return this.loadMatch.perform(matchId);\n  }\n}\n```\n`task.perform()` returns a `TaskInstance` which is a Promise-like object. Returning it from a method lets callers `await` the result directly or chain `.then()`. This pattern bridges tasks with non-task async code.",
  },
  {
    id: 45,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with a looping polling task",
    instruction: "How do I write a looping polling task in a service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class LiveScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked score = null;\n\n  pollScore = task({ restartable: true }, async (matchId) => {\n    while (true) {\n      try {\n        const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`);\n        if (response.ok) {\n          this.score = await response.json();\n        }\n      } catch { /* network error — continue */ }\n      await timeout(5000);\n    }\n  });\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    this.pollScore.cancelAll();\n  }\n}\n```\nAn infinite `while(true)` loop with `await timeout(N)` is the ember-concurrency polling pattern. The `restartable` modifier lets you restart with a new `matchId` cleanly. Always cancel in `willDestroy` to stop the loop on service teardown.",
  },
  {
    id: 46,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service exposing task.isRunning as a getter",
    instruction:
      "How do I expose a task's isRunning state as a named getter on the service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class MatchService extends Service {\n  loadMatch = task({ drop: true }, async (matchId) => {\n    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`);\n    return response.json();\n  });\n\n  get isLoading() {\n    return this.loadMatch.isRunning;\n  }\n\n  get lastError() {\n    return this.loadMatch.last?.error ?? null;\n  }\n}\n```\nWrapping `task.isRunning` in a named getter creates a semantic, readable API for consumers. `this.matchService.isLoading` reads better than `this.matchService.loadMatch.isRunning` in templates and other services.",
  },
  {
    id: 47,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with @tracked loading state managed by task",
    instruction:
      "Show me a service where a task manages the loading state via isRunning.",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class StandingsService extends Service {\n  @tracked standings = [];\n\n  fetchStandings = task({ drop: true }, async (tournamentId) => {\n    const response = await fetch(`/api/tournaments/${tournamentId}/standings`);\n    if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Failed to load standings');\n    const data = await response.json();\n    this.standings = data.teams;\n  });\n\n  get isLoading() {\n    return this.fetchStandings.isRunning;\n  }\n}\n```\nUsing `task.isRunning` instead of a manual `@tracked isLoading` is cleaner — the task automatically tracks its own running state. You never risk forgetting to set `isLoading = false` in an error path.",
  },
  {
    id: 48,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with @tracked error state managed by task",
    instruction: "How do I expose task error state reactively from a service?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class PlayerService extends Service {\n  @tracked players = [];\n\n  loadPlayers = task({ drop: true }, async (teamId) => {\n    const response = await fetch(`/api/teams/${teamId}/players`);\n    if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Could not load players');\n    this.players = await response.json();\n  });\n\n  get loadError() {\n    return this.loadPlayers.last?.error?.message ?? null;\n  }\n\n  get isError() {\n    return !!this.loadPlayers.last?.error;\n  }\n}\n```\n`task.last?.error` holds the error from the most recent task run. Using optional chaining guards against the case where no run has occurred yet (`task.last` is null initially). This gives consumers reactive error access without a separate `@tracked error` field.",
  },
  {
    id: 49,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service with @tracked data state populated by task",
    instruction:
      "Show me the full pattern of a service with data, loading, and error state all driven by a task.",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class MatchResultsService extends Service {\n  @tracked results = [];\n\n  loadResults = task({ drop: true }, async (tournamentId) => {\n    const response = await fetch(`/api/tournaments/${tournamentId}/results`);\n    if (!response.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);\n    const data = await response.json();\n    this.results = data.results ?? [];\n  });\n\n  get isLoading() { return this.loadResults.isRunning; }\n  get error()     { return this.loadResults.last?.error?.message ?? null; }\n  get hasData()   { return this.results.length > 0; }\n}\n```\nThis is the recommended full pattern: one `@tracked` field for data, and getters for `isLoading` and `error` derived from the task. Components consume `service.results`, `service.isLoading`, and `service.error` — all reactive without any manual state management.",
  },
  {
    id: 50,
    layer: "syntax",
    topic: "Service that registers itself as a global event listener",
    instruction:
      "How do I write a service that sets up and tears down a global event listener?",
    response:
      "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class KeyboardService extends Service {\n  @tracked lastKey = null;\n\n  #handlers = new Map();\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    this.#setupListeners();\n  }\n\n  #setupListeners() {\n    const onKeyDown = (event) => {\n      this.lastKey = event.key;\n      this.#handlers.get(event.key)?.();\n    };\n    this.#onKeyDown = onKeyDown;\n    window.addEventListener('keydown', onKeyDown);\n  }\n\n  registerShortcut(key, handler) {\n    this.#handlers.set(key, handler);\n  }\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    window.removeEventListener('keydown', this.#onKeyDown);\n    this.#handlers.clear();\n  }\n}\n```\nStoring the bound handler reference and the handlers map as private fields allows clean teardown in `willDestroy`. The service acts as a central keyboard shortcut registry for the entire application.",
  },

  {
    "id": 51,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Auth service — @tracked currentUser, isAuthenticated getter",
    "instruction": "How do I define an auth service with @tracked currentUser and an isAuthenticated getter?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class AuthService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentUser = null;\n\n  get isAuthenticated() {\n    return this.currentUser !== null;\n  }\n}\n```\nThe `@tracked` decorator on `currentUser` means any template or getter that reads it will automatically re-render when it changes. The `isAuthenticated` getter derives its value reactively — no `@tracked` is needed on the getter itself since it reads a tracked property."
  },
  {
    "id": 52,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Auth service — login task (POST credentials, set currentUser)",
    "instruction": "Show me a login task in an auth service that POSTs credentials and sets currentUser.",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class AuthService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentUser = null;\n\n  login = task(async (credentials) => {\n    const response = await fetch('/api/login', {\n      method: 'POST',\n      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },\n      body: JSON.stringify(credentials),\n    });\n    const data = await response.json();\n    this.currentUser = data.user;\n    return data.user;\n  });\n}\n```\nUsing `task` from ember-concurrency gives `.isRunning`, `.isError`, and cancellation for free. Pass credentials as `this.auth.login.perform({ email, password })`. Setting `this.currentUser` reactively updates all consuming components."
  },
  {
    "id": 53,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Auth service — logout method (clear currentUser, redirect)",
    "instruction": "How do I write a logout method in an auth service that clears currentUser and redirects?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class AuthService extends Service {\n  @service router;\n  @tracked currentUser = null;\n\n  logout() {\n    this.currentUser = null;\n    localStorage.removeItem('authToken');\n    this.router.transitionTo('login');\n  }\n}\n```\nThe `logout` method is synchronous — it clears `currentUser`, removes the persisted token from localStorage, and navigates away using the injected router service. Because `currentUser` is `@tracked`, all components checking `isAuthenticated` immediately re-render."
  },
  {
    "id": 54,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Auth service — token storage in plain property (not @tracked)",
    "instruction": "How do I store an auth token in a service property that is NOT reactive?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class AuthService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentUser = null;\n  token = null; // plain property — not reactive\n\n  setToken(token) {\n    this.token = token;\n    localStorage.setItem('authToken', token);\n  }\n\n  getToken() {\n    return this.token ?? localStorage.getItem('authToken');\n  }\n}\n```\nThe `token` property is intentionally NOT `@tracked` because no template ever needs to react to the raw token — it is used only in API headers. Only `currentUser` drives UI reactivity. Plain properties for non-UI state avoid unnecessary re-renders."
  },
  {
    "id": 55,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Auth service — refreshToken task",
    "instruction": "Show me a refreshToken task in an auth service.",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class AuthService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentUser = null;\n  token = null;\n\n  refreshToken = task(async () => {\n    const currentToken = localStorage.getItem('authToken');\n    const response = await fetch('/api/auth/refresh', {\n      method: 'POST',\n      headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${currentToken}` },\n    });\n    const { token, user } = await response.json();\n    this.token = token;\n    localStorage.setItem('authToken', token);\n    this.currentUser = user;\n    return token;\n  });\n}\n```\nThe `refreshToken` task sends the current token and replaces it with the new one. Add a `.drop()` modifier to prevent concurrent calls. Invoke with `this.auth.refreshToken.perform()`."
  },
  {
    "id": 56,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Auth service — isAdmin getter from currentUser role",
    "instruction": "How do I write an isAdmin getter on an auth service derived from currentUser.role?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class AuthService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentUser = null;\n\n  get isAdmin() {\n    return this.currentUser?.role === 'admin';\n  }\n\n  get isAuthenticated() {\n    return this.currentUser !== null;\n  }\n}\n```\nOptional chaining `?.` safely handles `null` currentUser. Because `isAdmin` reads the `@tracked` property `currentUser`, it recomputes whenever `currentUser` changes. No extra `@tracked` annotation is needed on the getter."
  },
  {
    "id": 57,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Notification service — @tracked notifications array",
    "instruction": "How do I set up a notification service with a @tracked notifications array?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class NotificationService extends Service {\n  @tracked notifications = [];\n}\n```\nThe `@tracked` on the array means Glimmer re-renders any template consuming `notifications` when the array reference changes. You must replace the array (not mutate in place) to trigger reactivity: use `this.notifications = [...this.notifications, newItem]` instead of `this.notifications.push(newItem)`."
  },
  {
    "id": 58,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Notification service — addNotification() method",
    "instruction": "How do I write an addNotification method in a notification service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class NotificationService extends Service {\n  @tracked notifications = [];\n\n  addNotification(message, type = 'info') {\n    const notification = {\n      id: crypto.randomUUID(),\n      message,\n      type,\n      createdAt: Date.now(),\n    };\n    this.notifications = [...this.notifications, notification];\n    return notification.id;\n  }\n}\n```\n`crypto.randomUUID()` generates a collision-free ID without dependencies. Spreading into a new array replaces the reference, triggering Glimmer reactivity. The method returns the `id` so callers can later dismiss the specific notification."
  },
  {
    "id": 59,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Notification service — removeNotification() method",
    "instruction": "How do I write a removeNotification method that dismisses by ID?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class NotificationService extends Service {\n  @tracked notifications = [];\n\n  removeNotification(id) {\n    this.notifications = this.notifications.filter((n) => n.id !== id);\n  }\n}\n```\n`Array.filter` always returns a new array, replacing `this.notifications` and triggering Glimmer reactivity. Safe to call even if the ID no longer exists — filter returns the array unchanged."
  },
  {
    "id": 60,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Notification service — clearAll() method",
    "instruction": "How do I add a clearAll method to a notification service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class NotificationService extends Service {\n  @tracked notifications = [];\n\n  clearAll() {\n    this.notifications = [];\n  }\n}\n```\nAssigning a fresh empty array replaces the reference, triggering reactivity — all consuming components re-render to show nothing. Simpler than filtering since no iteration is needed. Use on navigation or logout to reset notification state."
  },
  {
    "id": 61,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Notification service — auto-dismiss with task + timeout()",
    "instruction": "How do I auto-dismiss notifications after 5 seconds using an ember-concurrency task?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class NotificationService extends Service {\n  @tracked notifications = [];\n\n  addNotification(message, type = 'info', autoDismiss = true) {\n    const id = crypto.randomUUID();\n    this.notifications = [...this.notifications, { id, message, type }];\n    if (autoDismiss) this.autoDismiss.perform(id);\n    return id;\n  }\n\n  removeNotification(id) {\n    this.notifications = this.notifications.filter((n) => n.id !== id);\n  }\n\n  autoDismiss = task(async (id) => {\n    await timeout(5000);\n    this.removeNotification(id);\n  });\n}\n```\nUsing `timeout()` from ember-concurrency instead of `setTimeout` makes the delay cancellable. If the service is destroyed before 5 seconds, the running task is automatically cancelled — preventing calls on a destroyed service."
  },
  {
    "id": 62,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Router service — this.router.transitionTo() usage",
    "instruction": "How do I use the router service to navigate programmatically from another service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class AuthService extends Service {\n  @service router;\n\n  redirectToHome() {\n    this.router.transitionTo('home');\n  }\n\n  redirectToMatch(matchId) {\n    this.router.transitionTo('match', matchId);\n  }\n\n  redirectWithQuery() {\n    this.router.transitionTo('fixtures', { queryParams: { season: '2025' } });\n  }\n}\n```\nInject `router` using `@service` and call `transitionTo(routeName, ...models, options)`. The first argument is the route name, followed by optional dynamic segment values, and an options object for query params. Never use `window.location.href` in Ember."
  },
  {
    "id": 63,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Router service — this.router.currentRouteName getter",
    "instruction": "How do I read the current route name from the router service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class NavigationService extends Service {\n  @service router;\n\n  get currentRoute() {\n    return this.router.currentRouteName;\n  }\n\n  isOnRoute(routeName) {\n    return this.router.currentRouteName === routeName;\n  }\n\n  isOnMatchPage() {\n    return this.router.currentRouteName?.startsWith('match');\n  }\n}\n```\n`router.currentRouteName` returns a string like `'match.index'`. It is reactive — template reads update on navigation. The `startsWith` check handles nested routes. Use for active nav highlighting or conditional logic."
  },
  {
    "id": 64,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Router service — this.router.urlFor() to build URLs",
    "instruction": "How do I build a URL string without navigating, using the router service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class ShareService extends Service {\n  @service router;\n\n  getMatchUrl(matchId) {\n    return this.router.urlFor('match', matchId);\n  }\n\n  getShareLink(matchId) {\n    const path = this.router.urlFor('match', matchId);\n    return `${window.location.origin}${path}`;\n  }\n}\n```\n`urlFor` generates the URL string without triggering navigation — useful for share links and analytics. It takes the same arguments as `transitionTo`. Combine with `window.location.origin` to build absolute URLs."
  },
  {
    "id": 65,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Store service — store.findRecord() in component via injected store",
    "instruction": "How do I call store.findRecord() in a component using the injected store service?",
    "response": "```gjs\nimport Component from '@glimmer/component';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class PlayerProfileComponent extends Component {\n  @service store;\n\n  loadPlayer = task(async (playerId) => {\n    return await this.store.findRecord('player', playerId);\n  });\n\n  <template>\n    {{#if (this.loadPlayer.isRunning)}}\n      <p>Loading player...</p>\n    {{else if this.loadPlayer.value}}\n      <p>{{this.loadPlayer.value.name}}</p>\n    {{/if}}\n  </template>\n}\n```\n`store.findRecord('modelName', id)` fetches a single record by ID, returning a promise. Wrapping in a task gives you loading state. If the record is already cached in Ember Data, `findRecord` returns it immediately without a network request."
  },
  {
    "id": 66,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Store service — store.createRecord() + save() in service task",
    "instruction": "Show me how to create and save a new record using store.createRecord() inside a service task.",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class MatchService extends Service {\n  @service store;\n\n  createMatch = task(async (matchData) => {\n    const match = this.store.createRecord('match', {\n      venue: matchData.venue,\n      team1: matchData.team1,\n      team2: matchData.team2,\n      scheduledAt: matchData.scheduledAt,\n    });\n    await match.save();\n    return match;\n  });\n}\n```\n`store.createRecord` instantiates a new model in memory without persisting it. Calling `.save()` sends a POST request via the backend adapter. Wrapping in a task gives you `isRunning` and error state. The saved record is returned for further use."
  },
  {
    "id": 67,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Store service — store.peekAll() for cached data",
    "instruction": "How do I use store.peekAll() to get cached records without making a network request?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class PlayerService extends Service {\n  @service store;\n\n  getCachedPlayers() {\n    return this.store.peekAll('player');\n  }\n\n  getCachedPlayerById(id) {\n    return this.store.peekRecord('player', id);\n  }\n\n  get cachedPlayerCount() {\n    return this.store.peekAll('player').length;\n  }\n}\n```\n`peekAll` returns all records of a type currently in the identity map — no network request. `peekRecord` retrieves a single cached record by ID, returning `null` if not loaded. Use these after an initial `findAll` to read data synchronously."
  },
  {
    "id": 68,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Store service — store.unloadAll() in service cleanup",
    "instruction": "How do I unload all Ember Data records of a type in a service cleanup method?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class MatchService extends Service {\n  @service store;\n\n  clearMatchCache() {\n    this.store.unloadAll('match');\n  }\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    this.store.unloadAll('match');\n    this.store.unloadAll('player');\n  }\n}\n```\n`store.unloadAll(modelName)` removes all records of that type from the identity map without network requests. Useful in `willDestroy` to prevent stale data in tests. In production, call when switching tournaments to force fresh data on next load."
  },
  {
    "id": 69,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Session service — @tracked isLoggedIn, persist to localStorage",
    "instruction": "How do I create a session service with @tracked isLoggedIn that persists to localStorage?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class SessionService extends Service {\n  @tracked isLoggedIn = false;\n  @tracked userId = null;\n\n  establish(userId) {\n    this.isLoggedIn = true;\n    this.userId = userId;\n    localStorage.setItem('session', JSON.stringify({ isLoggedIn: true, userId }));\n  }\n\n  invalidate() {\n    this.isLoggedIn = false;\n    this.userId = null;\n    localStorage.removeItem('session');\n  }\n}\n```\nThe session service separates persistence (localStorage) from reactive state (`@tracked`). `establish` and `invalidate` keep both in sync. `@tracked isLoggedIn` drives template reactivity while localStorage survives page refreshes."
  },
  {
    "id": 70,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Session service — restore session from localStorage on init",
    "instruction": "How do I restore a session from localStorage when the session service initializes?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class SessionService extends Service {\n  @tracked isLoggedIn = false;\n  @tracked userId = null;\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    this.restoreSession();\n  }\n\n  restoreSession() {\n    try {\n      const raw = localStorage.getItem('session');\n      if (!raw) return;\n      const { isLoggedIn, userId } = JSON.parse(raw);\n      this.isLoggedIn = isLoggedIn ?? false;\n      this.userId = userId ?? null;\n    } catch {\n      localStorage.removeItem('session');\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\nThe `constructor` receives `owner` and `args` — always pass them to `super`. Wrap `JSON.parse` in try-catch to handle corrupted localStorage data gracefully. Nullish coalescing `??` provides safe defaults."
  },
  {
    "id": 71,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Session service — invalidate session (clear storage + @tracked)",
    "instruction": "How do I write a complete session invalidation method that clears both storage and tracked state?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class SessionService extends Service {\n  @service router;\n  @tracked isLoggedIn = false;\n  @tracked userId = null;\n  @tracked userRole = null;\n\n  invalidate() {\n    this.isLoggedIn = false;\n    this.userId = null;\n    this.userRole = null;\n    localStorage.removeItem('session');\n    sessionStorage.clear();\n    this.router.transitionTo('login');\n  }\n}\n```\nClear all `@tracked` fields first before calling `transitionTo` — any guards triggered by navigation will see the logged-out state immediately. Clear both localStorage and sessionStorage for full cleanup."
  },
  {
    "id": 72,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Feature flag service — @tracked flags object, isEnabled() method",
    "instruction": "How do I build a feature flag service with an isEnabled() method?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class FeatureFlagService extends Service {\n  @tracked flags = {\n    liveScore: true,\n    fantasyLeague: false,\n    videoHighlights: false,\n    darkMode: true,\n  };\n\n  isEnabled(flagName) {\n    return this.flags[flagName] ?? false;\n  }\n\n  enable(flagName) {\n    this.flags = { ...this.flags, [flagName]: true };\n  }\n\n  disable(flagName) {\n    this.flags = { ...this.flags, [flagName]: false };\n  }\n}\n```\nThe flags object must be replaced (not mutated) to trigger reactivity — spread `{ ...this.flags, [key]: value }` creates a new object. `isEnabled` returns `false` for unknown flags via `?? false` instead of `undefined`."
  },
  {
    "id": 73,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Analytics service — trackEvent() method (fire-and-forget task)",
    "instruction": "How do I write a trackEvent method in an analytics service that doesn't block the UI?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class AnalyticsService extends Service {\n  trackEvent(eventName, properties = {}) {\n    this._sendEvent.perform(eventName, properties);\n    // fire-and-forget: do not await\n  }\n\n  _sendEvent = task(async (eventName, properties) => {\n    await fetch('/api/analytics/events', {\n      method: 'POST',\n      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },\n      body: JSON.stringify({ event: eventName, properties, timestamp: Date.now() }),\n    });\n  });\n}\n```\n`trackEvent` is synchronous from the caller's perspective — it fires and forgets. Failures are silently ignored since analytics should never crash the app. Using a task over raw fetch ensures cleanup if the service is destroyed mid-request."
  },
  {
    "id": 74,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Analytics service — trackPageView() on router event",
    "instruction": "How do I track page views automatically by listening to router events in an analytics service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { service } from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class AnalyticsService extends Service {\n  @service router;\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    this.router.on('routeDidChange', this, this._onRouteChange);\n  }\n\n  _onRouteChange(transition) {\n    if (transition.to?.name) {\n      fetch('/api/analytics/pageview', {\n        method: 'POST',\n        body: JSON.stringify({ route: transition.to.name, timestamp: Date.now() }),\n        headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },\n      });\n    }\n  }\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    this.router.off('routeDidChange', this, this._onRouteChange);\n  }\n}\n```\nThe router emits `routeDidChange` after each successful navigation. Always deregister in `willDestroy` to prevent memory leaks. Pass `this` as context so `off()` can match the exact listener."
  },
  {
    "id": 75,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "WebSocket service — connection setup task, @tracked isConnected",
    "instruction": "How do I set up a WebSocket connection in a service with a @tracked isConnected property?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class WebSocketService extends Service {\n  @tracked isConnected = false;\n  _socket = null;\n\n  connect = task(async (url) => {\n    this._socket = new WebSocket(url);\n    await new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n      this._socket.onopen = () => { this.isConnected = true; resolve(); };\n      this._socket.onerror = reject;\n    });\n  });\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    this._socket?.close();\n    this.isConnected = false;\n  }\n}\n```\nThe `connect` task wraps `onopen` in a Promise so it can be awaited. `_socket` is a plain property (not `@tracked`) because the socket object itself doesn't drive templates. `isConnected` is tracked for reactive connection status display."
  },
  {
    "id": 76,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "WebSocket service — send() method",
    "instruction": "How do I write a send() method on a WebSocket service that safely checks connection state?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class WebSocketService extends Service {\n  @tracked isConnected = false;\n  _socket = null;\n\n  send(data) {\n    if (!this.isConnected || !this._socket) {\n      console.warn('WebSocket: attempted to send while disconnected');\n      return false;\n    }\n    const payload = typeof data === 'string' ? data : JSON.stringify(data);\n    this._socket.send(payload);\n    return true;\n  }\n}\n```\nAlways guard `send()` with a connection check — calling `socket.send()` on a closed socket throws. Auto-serialize objects to JSON. Returning a boolean lets callers detect if the message was actually sent."
  },
  {
    "id": 77,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "WebSocket service — @tracked messages array, onMessage handler",
    "instruction": "How do I store incoming WebSocket messages in a @tracked array?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class WebSocketService extends Service {\n  @tracked isConnected = false;\n  @tracked messages = [];\n  _socket = null;\n\n  _setupMessageHandler() {\n    this._socket.onmessage = (event) => {\n      const data = JSON.parse(event.data);\n      this.messages = [...this.messages, data];\n    };\n  }\n\n  get latestMessage() {\n    return this.messages.at(-1) ?? null;\n  }\n\n  clearMessages() {\n    this.messages = [];\n  }\n}\n```\nEach incoming message is spread into a new array — required for Glimmer reactivity. `Array.at(-1)` retrieves the last element cleanly. In a live cricket app each message might be a ball-by-ball update."
  },
  {
    "id": 78,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "WebSocket service — reconnect logic (looping task)",
    "instruction": "How do I implement automatic WebSocket reconnection using a looping ember-concurrency task?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class WebSocketService extends Service {\n  @tracked isConnected = false;\n  @tracked reconnectAttempts = 0;\n  _wsUrl = null;\n\n  reconnect = task(async () => {\n    while (true) {\n      await timeout(3000 * (this.reconnectAttempts + 1));\n      try {\n        await this.connect.perform(this._wsUrl);\n        this.reconnectAttempts = 0;\n        break;\n      } catch {\n        this.reconnectAttempts += 1;\n        if (this.reconnectAttempts >= 5) break;\n      }\n    }\n  });\n}\n```\nThe looping task retries with increasing delays (exponential back-off) up to 5 attempts. `timeout()` is cancellable — destroying the service during a wait stops the task cleanly. Reset `reconnectAttempts` on success."
  },
  {
    "id": 79,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "WebSocket service — willDestroy closes connection",
    "instruction": "How do I properly close a WebSocket connection when the service is destroyed?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class WebSocketService extends Service {\n  @tracked isConnected = false;\n  _socket = null;\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    if (this._socket) {\n      this._socket.onmessage = null;\n      this._socket.onerror = null;\n      this._socket.onclose = null;\n      this._socket.close(1000, 'Service destroyed');\n      this._socket = null;\n    }\n    this.isConnected = false;\n  }\n}\n```\nAlways call `super.willDestroy()` first. Null out handlers before closing to prevent final events calling back into the destroyed service. Close code `1000` signals normal closure. Setting `_socket = null` allows garbage collection."
  },
  {
    "id": 80,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Locale/i18n service — @tracked currentLocale, t() method stub",
    "instruction": "How do I create a basic locale service with @tracked currentLocale and a t() translation method?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nconst translations = {\n  en: { 'match.live': 'Live Match', 'player.runs': 'Runs' },\n  bn: { 'match.live': 'লাইভ ম্যাচ', 'player.runs': 'রান' },\n};\n\nexport default class LocaleService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentLocale = 'en';\n\n  t(key) {\n    return translations[this.currentLocale]?.[key] ?? key;\n  }\n\n  setLocale(locale) {\n    if (translations[locale]) this.currentLocale = locale;\n  }\n}\n```\nThe `t()` method falls back to the key itself if not found — safer than returning `undefined`. `setLocale` validates before switching. In production use `ember-intl` instead of this stub."
  },
  {
    "id": 81,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Theme service — @tracked currentTheme, toggle() method",
    "instruction": "How do I build a theme service with @tracked currentTheme and a toggle() method?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ThemeService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentTheme = 'light';\n\n  get isDark() {\n    return this.currentTheme === 'dark';\n  }\n\n  toggle() {\n    this.currentTheme = this.isDark ? 'light' : 'dark';\n  }\n\n  setTheme(theme) {\n    if (['light', 'dark'].includes(theme)) {\n      this.currentTheme = theme;\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n`toggle()` uses the `isDark` getter for clarity. `setTheme` validates input against allowed values. `currentTheme` being `@tracked` means any consuming component re-renders on change."
  },
  {
    "id": 82,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Theme service — persist theme to localStorage",
    "instruction": "How do I persist and restore the theme using localStorage in a theme service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ThemeService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentTheme = 'light';\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    const saved = localStorage.getItem('theme');\n    if (saved === 'light' || saved === 'dark') this.currentTheme = saved;\n  }\n\n  setTheme(theme) {\n    this.currentTheme = theme;\n    localStorage.setItem('theme', theme);\n  }\n\n  toggle() {\n    this.setTheme(this.currentTheme === 'dark' ? 'light' : 'dark');\n  }\n}\n```\nRestoring in the constructor ensures the correct theme loads before the first render. `setTheme` updates both `@tracked` state and localStorage — `toggle()` delegates to avoid duplicating persistence logic."
  },
  {
    "id": 83,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Theme service — apply theme class to document.body",
    "instruction": "How do I apply a theme class to document.body from a theme service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ThemeService extends Service {\n  @tracked currentTheme = 'light';\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    const saved = localStorage.getItem('theme') ?? 'light';\n    this.applyTheme(saved);\n  }\n\n  applyTheme(theme) {\n    this.currentTheme = theme;\n    document.body.classList.remove('theme-light', 'theme-dark');\n    document.body.classList.add(`theme-${theme}`);\n    localStorage.setItem('theme', theme);\n  }\n\n  toggle() {\n    this.applyTheme(this.currentTheme === 'dark' ? 'light' : 'dark');\n  }\n}\n```\n`classList.remove` both classes before adding prevents having both simultaneously. `applyTheme` co-locates all side effects. Works well with Tailwind's `dark:` variants when combined with a `dark` class on `body`."
  },
  {
    "id": 84,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Cart service — @tracked items array, addItem(), removeItem()",
    "instruction": "How do I build a cart service with addItem and removeItem methods?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class CartService extends Service {\n  @tracked items = [];\n\n  addItem(product) {\n    const existing = this.items.find((item) => item.id === product.id);\n    if (existing) {\n      this.items = this.items.map((item) =>\n        item.id === product.id ? { ...item, quantity: item.quantity + 1 } : item\n      );\n    } else {\n      this.items = [...this.items, { ...product, quantity: 1 }];\n    }\n  }\n\n  removeItem(productId) {\n    this.items = this.items.filter((item) => item.id !== productId);\n  }\n}\n```\n`addItem` checks for an existing item to increment quantity rather than add a duplicate. `map` returns a new array for reactivity. `removeItem` uses `filter`. Both always replace `this.items` for Glimmer change detection."
  },
  {
    "id": 85,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Cart service — getter totalPrice computed from items",
    "instruction": "How do I write a totalPrice getter in a cart service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class CartService extends Service {\n  @tracked items = [];\n\n  get totalPrice() {\n    return this.items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price * item.quantity, 0);\n  }\n\n  get formattedTotalPrice() {\n    return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD' }).format(this.totalPrice);\n  }\n}\n```\nBecause `totalPrice` reads `@tracked items`, it recomputes automatically when items change. `Intl.NumberFormat` formats currency natively without any library. Both getters are usable directly in GJS templates."
  },
  {
    "id": 86,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Cart service — getter itemCount",
    "instruction": "How do I write an itemCount getter that returns the total number of items in a cart service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class CartService extends Service {\n  @tracked items = [];\n\n  get itemCount() {\n    return this.items.reduce((total, item) => total + item.quantity, 0);\n  }\n\n  get isEmpty() {\n    return this.itemCount === 0;\n  }\n\n  get uniqueItemCount() {\n    return this.items.length;\n  }\n}\n```\n`itemCount` sums all quantities while `uniqueItemCount` returns distinct products. Both read `@tracked items` so they re-evaluate reactively. `isEmpty` drives the empty cart UI state."
  },
  {
    "id": 87,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Cart service — clear() method",
    "instruction": "How do I add a clear() method to a cart service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class CartService extends Service {\n  @tracked items = [];\n  @tracked couponCode = null;\n\n  clear() {\n    this.items = [];\n    this.couponCode = null;\n  }\n\n  clearAfterCheckout() {\n    this.clear();\n    localStorage.removeItem('cart');\n  }\n}\n```\nAssigning `[]` replaces the array reference triggering reactivity. `clear()` resets all cart state including coupon codes. `clearAfterCheckout` adds cleanup of any persisted cart state."
  },
  {
    "id": 88,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Modal service — @tracked isOpen, @tracked modalComponent",
    "instruction": "How do I set up a modal service with @tracked isOpen and @tracked modalComponent?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ModalService extends Service {\n  @tracked isOpen = false;\n  @tracked modalComponent = null;\n  @tracked modalOptions = {};\n\n  get hasModal() {\n    return this.isOpen && this.modalComponent !== null;\n  }\n}\n```\n`modalComponent` stores the name or class of the component to render inside the modal host. `modalOptions` passes configuration to the modal. `hasModal` is a safety getter to avoid rendering when nothing is set."
  },
  {
    "id": 89,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Modal service — open(componentName, options) method",
    "instruction": "How do I write an open() method on a modal service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ModalService extends Service {\n  @tracked isOpen = false;\n  @tracked modalComponent = null;\n  @tracked modalOptions = {};\n\n  open(componentName, options = {}) {\n    this.modalComponent = componentName;\n    this.modalOptions = options;\n    this.isOpen = true;\n  }\n}\n```\nSet `modalComponent` and `modalOptions` before `isOpen = true` to avoid a render cycle where the modal host tries to render without knowing which component to show. The `options` object can include any props like `{ matchId: '123', title: 'Match Details' }`."
  },
  {
    "id": 90,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Modal service — close() method",
    "instruction": "How do I write a close() method on a modal service that also runs a callback?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ModalService extends Service {\n  @tracked isOpen = false;\n  @tracked modalComponent = null;\n  @tracked modalOptions = {};\n  _onClose = null;\n\n  open(componentName, options = {}, onClose = null) {\n    this.modalComponent = componentName;\n    this.modalOptions = options;\n    this._onClose = onClose;\n    this.isOpen = true;\n  }\n\n  close(result = null) {\n    this.isOpen = false;\n    const callback = this._onClose;\n    this._onClose = null;\n    this.modalComponent = null;\n    this.modalOptions = {};\n    callback?.(result);\n  }\n}\n```\nThe optional `onClose` callback lets callers react to modal results. Clearing `_onClose` before calling it prevents double-invocation. Setting `isOpen = false` before clearing `modalComponent` gives close animations time to complete."
  },
  {
    "id": 91,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Toast service — @tracked toasts array, show(message, type)",
    "instruction": "How do I build a toast service with a show() method?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ToastService extends Service {\n  @tracked toasts = [];\n\n  show(message, type = 'info', duration = 4000) {\n    const toast = { id: crypto.randomUUID(), message, type, duration };\n    this.toasts = [...this.toasts, toast];\n    if (duration > 0) setTimeout(() => this.dismiss(toast.id), duration);\n    return toast.id;\n  }\n\n  dismiss(id) {\n    this.toasts = this.toasts.filter((t) => t.id !== id);\n  }\n}\n```\n`duration = 0` disables auto-dismiss for persistent toasts. `crypto.randomUUID()` gives collision-free IDs. The `type` field maps to Tailwind classes for color coding (green=success, red=error)."
  },
  {
    "id": 92,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Toast service — dismiss(id) method",
    "instruction": "How do I write a dismiss method for a toast service that removes by ID?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ToastService extends Service {\n  @tracked toasts = [];\n\n  dismiss(id) {\n    this.toasts = this.toasts.filter((toast) => toast.id !== id);\n  }\n\n  dismissAll() {\n    this.toasts = [];\n  }\n}\n```\n`filter` returns a new array excluding the dismissed toast, replacing `this.toasts` and triggering reactivity. `dismissAll` is a one-liner that resets to empty. Both are safe to call with non-existent IDs."
  },
  {
    "id": 93,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Toast service — success(), error(), warning() convenience methods",
    "instruction": "How do I add convenience methods like success(), error(), and warning() to a toast service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ToastService extends Service {\n  @tracked toasts = [];\n\n  show(message, type = 'info', duration = 4000) {\n    const id = crypto.randomUUID();\n    this.toasts = [...this.toasts, { id, message, type }];\n    if (duration > 0) setTimeout(() => this.dismiss(id), duration);\n    return id;\n  }\n\n  dismiss(id) { this.toasts = this.toasts.filter((t) => t.id !== id); }\n  success(msg, duration = 4000) { return this.show(msg, 'success', duration); }\n  error(msg, duration = 0) { return this.show(msg, 'error', duration); }\n  warning(msg, duration = 6000) { return this.show(msg, 'warning', duration); }\n  info(msg, duration = 4000) { return this.show(msg, 'info', duration); }\n}\n```\nConvenience methods delegate to `show()` with type-specific defaults — errors persist (`duration = 0`) while info toasts auto-dismiss. Each returns the toast ID for programmatic dismissal."
  },
  {
    "id": 94,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Clipboard service — copy(text) task using navigator.clipboard",
    "instruction": "How do I write a clipboard service with a copy task using the native Clipboard API?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class ClipboardService extends Service {\n  @tracked isCopied = false;\n\n  copy = task(async (text) => {\n    await navigator.clipboard.writeText(text);\n    this.isCopied = true;\n    await timeout(2000);\n    this.isCopied = false;\n  });\n}\n```\n`navigator.clipboard.writeText()` is Promise-based and requires a secure context (HTTPS or localhost). `isCopied` flips to `true` for 2 seconds to drive 'Copied!' UI feedback, then resets. Using `timeout()` makes the reset cancellable."
  },
  {
    "id": 95,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Scroll service — @tracked scrollTop, setup scroll listener in constructor",
    "instruction": "How do I create a scroll service that tracks scrollTop using a window event listener?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ScrollService extends Service {\n  @tracked scrollTop = 0;\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    this._onScroll = () => { this.scrollTop = window.scrollY; };\n    window.addEventListener('scroll', this._onScroll, { passive: true });\n  }\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    window.removeEventListener('scroll', this._onScroll);\n  }\n}\n```\n`{ passive: true }` tells the browser the listener won't call `preventDefault()`, enabling scroll optimizations. Store the handler on `this._onScroll` so `removeEventListener` can identify the exact function to remove."
  },
  {
    "id": 96,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Scroll service — scrollTo(element) method",
    "instruction": "How do I add a scrollTo() method to a scroll service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\n\nexport default class ScrollService extends Service {\n  scrollTo(element, options = {}) {\n    if (!element) return;\n    element.scrollIntoView({ behavior: options.behavior ?? 'smooth', block: options.block ?? 'start' });\n  }\n\n  scrollToTop(behavior = 'smooth') {\n    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior });\n  }\n\n  scrollToId(elementId, options = {}) {\n    const el = document.getElementById(elementId);\n    this.scrollTo(el, options);\n  }\n}\n```\n`scrollIntoView` is native and handles cross-browser concerns. `scrollToId` is a convenience wrapper for common use cases. Guard against null `element` to prevent errors when the element hasn't rendered yet."
  },
  {
    "id": 97,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Breakpoint service — @tracked isMobile based on window.innerWidth",
    "instruction": "How do I build a breakpoint service that tracks isMobile based on screen width?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class BreakpointService extends Service {\n  @tracked isMobile = window.innerWidth < 768;\n  @tracked isTablet = window.innerWidth >= 768 && window.innerWidth < 1024;\n  @tracked isDesktop = window.innerWidth >= 1024;\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    this._onResize = () => this._update();\n    window.addEventListener('resize', this._onResize, { passive: true });\n  }\n\n  _update() {\n    const w = window.innerWidth;\n    this.isMobile = w < 768;\n    this.isTablet = w >= 768 && w < 1024;\n    this.isDesktop = w >= 1024;\n  }\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    window.removeEventListener('resize', this._onResize);\n  }\n}\n```\nBreakpoint values match Tailwind's default breakpoints (md: 768px, lg: 1024px). All three are `@tracked` so components re-render on resize. Initialization captures the correct initial value before any resize events."
  },
  {
    "id": 98,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Breakpoint service — resize listener setup and teardown",
    "instruction": "How do I use ResizeObserver in a breakpoint service for better performance?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class BreakpointService extends Service {\n  @tracked width = window.innerWidth;\n  _resizeObserver = null;\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    this._resizeObserver = new ResizeObserver(() => {\n      this.width = window.innerWidth;\n    });\n    this._resizeObserver.observe(document.documentElement);\n  }\n\n  get isMobile() { return this.width < 768; }\n  get isDesktop() { return this.width >= 1024; }\n\n  willDestroy() {\n    super.willDestroy();\n    this._resizeObserver?.disconnect();\n    this._resizeObserver = null;\n  }\n}\n```\n`ResizeObserver` on `document.documentElement` is more performant than `window.resize`. `.disconnect()` in `willDestroy` removes all observed targets. `_resizeObserver` is nulled after disconnecting for garbage collection."
  },
  {
    "id": 99,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Permission service — @tracked permissions array, can(action) method",
    "instruction": "How do I build a permission service with a can() method that checks an array of permissions?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class PermissionService extends Service {\n  @tracked permissions = [];\n\n  can(action) {\n    return this.permissions.includes(action);\n  }\n\n  canAny(actions) {\n    return actions.some((action) => this.can(action));\n  }\n\n  canAll(actions) {\n    return actions.every((action) => this.can(action));\n  }\n\n  setPermissions(permissions) {\n    this.permissions = [...permissions];\n  }\n}\n```\n`can('edit:match')` checks if the string is in the permissions array. `canAny` returns true if at least one permission matches (OR logic). `canAll` requires all (AND logic). Permission strings follow `action:resource` convention."
  },
  {
    "id": 100,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Permission service — fetch permissions task on init",
    "instruction": "How do I fetch user permissions from an API when the permission service initializes?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class PermissionService extends Service {\n  @tracked permissions = [];\n  @tracked isLoading = true;\n  @tracked error = null;\n\n  constructor(owner, args) {\n    super(owner, args);\n    this.fetchPermissions.perform();\n  }\n\n  fetchPermissions = task(async () => {\n    try {\n      this.isLoading = true;\n      this.error = null;\n      const response = await fetch('/api/user/permissions');\n      const { permissions } = await response.json();\n      this.permissions = permissions;\n    } catch (err) {\n      this.error = err.message;\n    } finally {\n      this.isLoading = false;\n    }\n  });\n\n  can(action) {\n    return this.permissions.includes(action);\n  }\n}\n```\nTriggering `fetchPermissions.perform()` in the constructor means permissions load as soon as the service is first injected. `isLoading` lets components show a skeleton state. `finally` ensures `isLoading` resets even on error."
  },
  {
    "id": 101,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Cricket score service — @tracked liveScore object, fetch task",
    "instruction": "How do I create a cricket score service with a @tracked liveScore object and a fetch task?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class ScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked liveScore = null;\n  @tracked isLoading = false;\n\n  fetchScore = task(async (matchId) => {\n    this.isLoading = true;\n    try {\n      const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`);\n      this.liveScore = await response.json();\n    } finally {\n      this.isLoading = false;\n    }\n  });\n}\n```\n`liveScore` starts as `null` so components can show an empty state. The `finally` block guarantees `isLoading` resets even if the fetch throws. Using a task instead of plain async gives `.isRunning`, `.lastError`, and cancellation."
  },
  {
    "id": 102,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Cricket score service — updateScore() method",
    "instruction": "How do I write an updateScore method in a cricket score service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked liveScore = null;\n\n  updateScore(scoreData) {\n    this.liveScore = { ...this.liveScore, ...scoreData, updatedAt: Date.now() };\n  }\n\n  addRuns(runs) {\n    if (!this.liveScore) return;\n    this.liveScore = { ...this.liveScore, totalRuns: (this.liveScore.totalRuns ?? 0) + runs };\n  }\n\n  incrementWickets() {\n    if (!this.liveScore) return;\n    this.liveScore = { ...this.liveScore, wickets: (this.liveScore.wickets ?? 0) + 1 };\n  }\n}\n```\nSpread syntax merges incoming data and creates a new reference — required for reactivity. Guard each method with null check to prevent errors when called before data loads."
  },
  {
    "id": 103,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Cricket score service — startPolling() / stopPolling() task control",
    "instruction": "How do I implement startPolling and stopPolling in a cricket score service?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\nimport { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency';\n\nexport default class ScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked liveScore = null;\n  @tracked isPolling = false;\n\n  pollScore = task(async (matchId) => {\n    this.isPolling = true;\n    try {\n      while (true) {\n        const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`);\n        this.liveScore = await response.json();\n        await timeout(10000);\n      }\n    } finally {\n      this.isPolling = false;\n    }\n  });\n\n  startPolling(matchId) { this.pollScore.perform(matchId); }\n  stopPolling() { this.pollScore.cancelAll(); }\n}\n```\nThe infinite `while (true)` loop combined with `cancelAll()` is the idiomatic ember-concurrency polling pattern. `timeout()` is cancellable — stopping during the wait cleans up immediately. `isPolling` in `finally` resets on both stop and error."
  },
  {
    "id": 104,
    "layer": "syntax",
    "topic": "Cricket score service — getter currentInnings from liveScore",
    "instruction": "How do I write a currentInnings getter on a score service derived from liveScore?",
    "response": "```js\nimport Service from '@ember/service';\nimport { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';\n\nexport default class ScoreService extends Service {\n  @tracked liveScore = null;\n\n  get currentInnings() { return this.liveScore?.currentInnings ?? 1; }\n  get battingTeam() { return this.liveScore?.battingTeam ?? null; }\n  get bowlingTeam() { return this.liveScore?.bowlingTeam ?? null; }\n  get currentOver() { return this.liveScore?.over ?? '0.0'; }\n}\n```\nOptional chaining `?.` safely navigates null `liveScore` before data loads. `?? 1` defaults to the first innings. These getters are reactive because they read `@tracked liveScore` — when score updates, all derived getters recompute."
  },
  {
